        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-container">
            <h3>Why did calculating 65 mph × 3.15 yield the wrong distance?</h3>
            <p>Because human clocks operate strictly on Base-60 and standard math operates on Base-10. 15 literal minutes does NOT equal the decimal 0.15. 15 minutes is mathematically exactly one quarter (0.25) of a whole hour. You must safely convert minutes via division (X / 60) before applying the distance equation.</p>
            
            <h3>What if my travel speed constantly heavily fluctuates?</h3>
            <p>If you are driving in stop-and-go traffic, utilizing a static 65 mph variable fails immediately. You must determine your Average Speed across the entire duration by combining fast spurts with stagnant stopping, then apply the distance formula exclusively to the mathematically smoothed average.</p>
            
            <h3>Can I use this to track hiking and running logic?</h3>
            <p>Absolutely. The formula is fundamentally universal to all kinetic motion. If you steadily hike at roughly 3.5 miles per hour for approximately 4 straight hours, you are mathematically guaranteed to cover 14 total miles of ground.</p>
        </div>

